description:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;OPERATIONAL TEAM LEADER:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Salary: &lt;/strong&gt;Band 7 - £38,890 to £44,503 + Unsocial Hours&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Locations: &lt;/strong&gt; Dartford &amp; Medway Operating Unit&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Contract length: Permanent &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;We are looking for suitable applicants to join our existing operational team leaders within Medway and Dartford Operating Unit. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Applications are invited from highly motivated, operationally focused HCPC registered clinicians looking for the challenge to develop and lead an effective operational team, ensuring the delivery of clinical and non-clinical KPI’s to the respective Operating Unit area.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Operational Team Leaders will provide a core of effective leadership, clinical and management support for their team including maintaining their welfare, supporting personal development and reviewing performance and progress. You will also be expected to perform Operational Command (formerly Bronze Command) duties that include large scale and major incidents.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In order to apply, you must have successfully completed a minimum of two years as a practicing HCPC registered clinician in a front line delivery Emergency focused role (at application). You will have the passion and drive to support your team to deliver the highest levels of patient care and clinical safety. This role will require excellent communication skills, flexibility and a high degree of personal organisation to determine priorities and the ability to handle a range of issues. You will need to be an excellent problem solver, demonstrating flexibility in your approach to the changing priorities the Trust faces on a day-to-day basis. These aforementioned attributes are integral to the role.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If successful at assessment and offered a position; you will begin your journey as an Operational Team Leader and be assigned to an operational area to manage a team within the Trust.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Requirements: &lt;/strong&gt;In order to apply, you must be able to successfully evidence completion of a minimum of two years (post registration) clinical paramedic practice (at application).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We encourage staff who are considering applying to spend time with an OTL to gain a good understanding of the role.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It is the applicants’ responsibility to make sure they are available to attend the dates relevant. If you are not able to attend, your application will be withdrawn. Due to operational demand, staff will not be abstracted from shifts. Please ensure you make any necessary arrangements to attend as soon as possible.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you are a current SECAmb employee, by applying for this position, if successful you will move to the terms and conditions associated with the post. Any unsocial hours payments will be paid under the Section 2 agreement of agenda for change. Section 2 unsocial hours will need to be claimed via your monthly timesheet. More information regarding section 2 can be found in the Agenda for Change handbook and on the our dedicated Section 2 page on The Zone .&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For more information about the Operational Team Leader role, please contact Laurence Sopp Operations Manager (Dartford) via Laurence.sopp@secamb.nhs.uk or Matthew Pankhurst Operations Manager (Swale) Matthew.pankhurst@secamb.nhs.uk&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For further details / informal visits contact:&lt;/p&gt;
